UMUAHIA – The Federal Government has embarked on the training and empowerment of Women and Youths smallholder farmers of Omoba in Isiala Ngwa South Council Area under Isiala Ngwa South and North Federal Constituency of Abia State on cassava value chain production at National Soil Laboratory, FMARD, Umuahia, Speaking during the training, the Abia State Director, Federal Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development (FMARD) Mr. Victor Ihediwa said the Federal Government is diligently working towards achieving food and nutrition security through its various activities by using a combination of policies and appropriate Agricultural technologies that would lead to job and wealth creation as well as improve living standards. “This is part of its efforts to ensure that the yield gap in cassava is addressed through dissemination and adoption of improved technologies as well as innovation by smallholder farmers. Kanu: IPOB, Urges Ndigbo To Storm Umuahia High Court On… Dangote, Emefiele Commend Ogun As Investment-Friendly He explained that under the training programme, the cassava farmers were exposed to how best to grow a good cassava crop which includes: good site selection; proper land preparation; choosing desirable/ improved varieties; healthy cassava stems selection, high yielding resistant varieties among other best practices. He said one of the FMARD methods through which the Department of Agricultural Extension is working to achieve this objective was through the promotion of various crops such as cassava in which Nigeria has the comparative advantage in production.